   "source": [
    "# 30. Explain Pruning in Decision Trees and how it is done"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0504dff8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "✅ What is Pruning in Decision Trees?\n",
    "\n",
    "Pruning is the process of removing unnecessary branches from a decision tree to reduce complexity and prevent overfitting.\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 A fully grown tree:\n",
    "\n",
    "Fits training data very well\n",
    "But captures noise ❌\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Pruning:\n",
    "\n",
    "Simplifies the tree\n",
    "Improves generalization\n",
    "🎯 Why is Pruning Needed?\n",
    "Reduces overfitting (high variance)\n",
    "Makes model simpler & interpretable\n",
    "Improves performance on unseen data\n",
    "✅ Types of Pruning\n",
    "🔹 1. Pre-Pruning (Early Stopping)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Stop tree growth before it becomes too complex\n",
    "\n",
    "Techniques:\n",
    "Limit max depth\n",
    "Set minimum samples per split\n",
    "Set minimum samples per leaf\n",
    "Use information gain threshold\n",
    "\n",
    "✔️ Faster\n",
    "❌ May lead to underfitting\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 2. Post-Pruning (Most Important)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 First grow full tree → then prune\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Cost Complexity Pruning (Widely used)\n",
    "\n",
    "R\n",
    "α\n",
    "\t​\n",
    "\n",
    "(T)=R(T)+α⋅∣T∣\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "\n",
    "R(T): training error\n",
    "∣T∣: number of leaf nodes\n",
    "α: complexity penalty\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Objective:\n",
    "\n",
    "Balance accuracy vs complexity\n",
    "How it works:\n",
    "Build full tree\n",
    "Remove weakest branches (least useful splits)\n",
    "Choose optimal tree using validation data\n",
    "🚀 Real-world Implementation\n",
    "\n",
    "In Scikit-learn:\n",
    "\n",
    "Use parameter: ccp_alpha\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier\n",
    "\n",
    "model = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=0.01)\n",
    "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "🎯 Interview-Ready Answer (Short)**\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “Pruning in decision trees is used to reduce overfitting by removing unnecessary branches. It can be done using pre-pruning techniques like limiting tree depth or post-pruning methods like cost-complexity pruning, which balances model accuracy and complexity.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Pro Tip\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “Post-pruning is generally more effective than pre-pruning because it evaluates the full tree before simplifying it.”"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7a0b3811",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 1. Visualization: Pruned vs Unpruned Tree"
