   "source": [
    "# 2. Entropy vs Gini (Very Important Interview Topic)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "e0b4725f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Both are used to measure impurity in decision trees.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Entropy (Information Gain - used in ID3, C4.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "Entropy=−∑p\n",
    "i\n",
    "\t​\n",
    "\n",
    "log\n",
    "2\n",
    "\t​\n",
    "\n",
    "p\n",
    "i\n",
    "\t​\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Properties:\n",
    "Range: 0 to 1\n",
    "0 → pure node\n",
    "Higher → more disorder\n",
    "🔹 Gini Index (used in CART)\n",
    "\n",
    "Gini=1−∑p\n",
    "i\n",
    "2\n",
    "\t​\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Properties:\n",
    "Range: 0 to 0.5 (binary case)\n",
    "Lower = better split\n",
    "🔥 Entropy vs Gini (Comparison)\n",
    "Aspect\tEntropy\tGini\n",
    "Formula\tLog-based\tSquare-based\n",
    "Speed\tSlower\tFaster\n",
    "Use\tID3, C4.5\tCART (most common)\n",
    "Sensitivity\tMore sensitive\tLess sensitive\n",
    "Preference\tTheoretical\tPractical\n",
    "🎯 Interview Line\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 “Gini is computationally faster, so it’s preferred in most real-world implementations.”"
   ]
  },
